SIMPLE: probe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Probe
<hw>Probe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Probed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Probing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>probare</ets> to try,
examine. See <er>Prove</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To examine, as a wound, an ulcer, or some cavity of
the body, with a probe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: to search to the bottom; to scrutinize or
examine thoroughly.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The growing disposition to <qex>probe</qex> the legality of all
acts, of the crown.</q> <rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Probe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Probe
<hw>Probe</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An instrument for
examining the depth or other circumstances of a wound, ulcer, or cavity,
or the direction of a sinus, of for exploring for bullets, for stones in
the bladder, etc.</def> <rj><au>Parr.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Probe scissors</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Probe-pointed scissors</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Surg.)</fld>,
<cd>scissors used to open wounds, the blade of which, to be thrust into
the orifice, has a button at the end.</cd>
<rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Probeagle</ent>⟦br⟧
